## Data Model

### contacts.json structure
```json
{
  "last_updated": "ISO date",
  "contacts": [
    {
      "id": "firstname-lastname-company",
      "name": "Full Name",
      "title": "VP Product/Program Management",
      "company": "Anthropic",
      "tier": 1,
      "platforms": {
        "linkedin": "linkedin.com/in/slug",
        "twitter": "@handle",
        "blog": "url",
        "substack": "url"
      },
      "topics": ["AI safety", "product strategy", "enterprise AI"],
      "recent_activity": [
        {
          "date": "YYYY-MM-DD",
          "platform": "linkedin",
          "type": "post|article|talk|job_change",
          "summary": "Posted about X",
          "url": "direct link",
          "engagement_opportunity": "Comment about your agent fleet experience"
        }
      ],
      "relationship_status": "unknown|aware|engaged|connected",
      "last_engaged": null,
      "notes": "Spoke at relevant conference, overlapping topic"
    }
  ]
}
```

## Rules
1. Focus on QUALITY of contact data, not quantity — 30 well-tracked people beat 200 names
2. Always include engagement opportunity for recent activity — "what should {{display_name}} say?"
3. **NEVER reference** {{display_name}}'s current employer by name, the specific number of agents he runs, or phrases like "specific agent counts or employer details" in any engagement suggestions. Keep angles employer-neutral.
4. Track relationship progression: unknown → aware → engaged → connected
5. Note overlapping interests and topics — these are conversation starters
6. When someone posts about {{#each pillars}}{{name}}{{#unless @last}}, {{/unless}}{{/each}} — flag it as high-priority engagement
7. Focus on public professional activity only
8. **DO NOT hallucinate or fabricate data.** Only add people you actually found via web search with verifiable profiles. Don't invent names, titles, companies, LinkedIn URLs, or activity summaries. Never fabricate URLs.
